edict  ).","French (<b>Bénac</b>): habitational name from any of the places in Ariège and Hautes-Pyrénées named Bénac, from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Benos</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]}]},{"name":"Gaillard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Philippe, Pierre, Andre, Andree, Ketly, Marcel, Mirlande, Monique.","French: nickname from <i>gaillard</i> ‘vigorous, strong’ (ultimately from Celtic <i>galia</i> ‘strength’). This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gailhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>gail</i> ‘powerful, lusty, cheerful’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gailliard","meanings":["French: variant of   Gaillard   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Gaylord","meanings":["Transferred use of a surname, which is a form, altered by folk etymology, of the Old French nickname <i>Gaillard</i> ‘dandy’. It was adopted as a first name from the 19th century, but it now seems to have suffered the same fate as <i>Gay</i> (  see  Gaye  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gaillard de Beynac was born in Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France as the son of Gaillard II de Beynac and Helene Gratienne. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1310, in Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France."},"et":{"–about 1310":"–umbes 1310","1255–1300":"1255–1300","–1310":"–1310","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–1338":"–1338","–1360":"–1360","1230–1274":"1230–1274","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1338":"1338","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","about 1310":"umbes 1310","Aft 1274":"pärast 1274","1360":"1360","Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Beynac, Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–about 1310":"–noin 1310","1255–1300":"1255–1300","–1310":"–1310","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","–1338":"–1338","–1360":"–1360","1230–1274":"1230–1274","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1338":"1338","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","about 1310":"noin 1310","Aft 1274":"1274 jälkeen","1360":"1360","Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Ranska","Beynac, Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska"},"fr":{"–about 1310":"–environ 1310","1255–1300":"1255–1300","–1310":"–1310","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","–1338":"–1338","–1360":"–1360","1230–1274":"1230–1274","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1338":"1338","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","about 1310":"environ 1310","Aft 1274":"après 1274","1360":"